      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes way more sense. thanks. i remember reading somewhere that einstein called it \"spooky action at a distance\" because it seemed so weird. why did he call it spooky though? like what exactly is the \"spooky\" part of the physics?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Einstein referred to quantum entanglement as \"spooky action at a distance\" because it seemed to violate the principles of classical physics, particularly the idea that nothing can travel faster than the speed of light. In the classical view, objects are only influenced by their immediate surroundings, and any influence would be limited by the speed of light, as per the theory of relativity. However, quantum entanglement suggests that two particles can be instantaneously correlated, regardless of the distance separating them, which implies a form of communication that defies the known limits of space and time.\n\nEinstein found this concept counterintuitive and unsettling because it seemed to imply a hidden connection between particles that could not be explained by the existing laws of physics. He was a firm believer in the completeness of quantum mechanics and was uncomfortable with the idea that the theory might be incomplete or that there could be hidden variables at play. The \"spooky\" part, therefore, refers to the mysterious and seemingly paradoxical nature of entanglement, which challenged the very foundations of classical physics and our understanding of the universe. Despite his reservations, subsequent experiments have confirmed the reality of quantum entanglement, solidifying its place as a fundamental aspect of quantum mechanics.",
      "source": "target",
